## Suggested Fix

1. After email submission, dispatch a verification link to the provided address **before** issuing any `idToken` or session token.
2. Display an on-screen message: *"We've sent a verification link to your email. Please check your inbox to continue."*
3. Block all access — including browsing, content playback, and purchase flows — until the verification link has been clicked and confirmed.
4. Enforce `emailVerified: true` **server-side** before generating and returning an `idToken`. Do not rely solely on client-side checks.
5. Set the Firestore user record to a `status: "pending"` state until verification is complete — do not write an active record on first submission.
6. Expire unverified accounts after 48 hours to maintain database hygiene.

---

## Notes

- My Muse does not use passwords — email is the sole identifier. This makes the absence of verification a higher risk than in a password-based system.
- This bug was found during **first-time sign-in testing only**. Whether returning users face the same issue is to be verified in a separate test case.
- `send_emails: true` in the server response confirms the email infrastructure is active and capable of sending — the verification email is simply never triggered.
- Additional out-of-scope findings observed during this session (email in URL query string, pre-auth request on modal open, internal config over-exposure) have been noted in WEB-TC-001 and will be filed as separate bugs.
